        <!-- Key Principles -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Key Principles for AI Tool Adoption</h2>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Start with pain points, not hype</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Ask: "What repetitive task is eating my team's time?" not "What's the trendiest AI tool?" The best AI adoption is problem-driven, not technology-driven.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">One tool at a time</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Adopt, learn, measure value, then add the next one. Trying to implement 10 tools simultaneously means none get properly embedded in your workflow.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Free tiers first, always</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Almost every tool here has a free tier. Use it for 2-4 weeks before upgrading. If you're not hitting the limits of the free tier, you probably don't need the paid version yet.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">AI augments, it doesn't replace</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Use AI as a first draft, not a final product. Human review, editing, and judgement still matter. The most effective approach: AI does 80% of the work, humans refine the last 20%.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Consolidate where possible</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Fewer tools doing more is better than many tools doing little. ChatGPT can handle writing, research, analysis, and basic code. Don't buy five specialised tools when one general one covers 80% of use cases.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">The businesses getting ahead with AI in 2026 aren't the ones with the most tools — they're the ones using a few tools deeply. Pick the right ones for your specific needs, embed them in daily workflows, and measure the time and money they save. That's the path from "AI-curious" to "AI-powered."</p>

